1
00:00:06,565 --> 00:00:08,347
All right, so we're talking about playgrounds

2
00:00:08,447 --> 00:00:10,148
and level design, applying playgrounds.

3
00:00:11,229 --> 00:00:13,411
Briefly about me, my background's in modding,

4
00:00:13,471 --> 00:00:14,532
which will be relevant later,

5
00:00:14,812 --> 00:00:16,914
and I also work as a multiplayer level designer,

6
00:00:16,934 --> 00:00:18,935
including these games and some others.

7
00:00:19,415 --> 00:00:20,977
But we're here to talk about playgrounds,

8
00:00:21,217 --> 00:00:22,158
real-world playgrounds,

9
00:00:22,178 --> 00:00:23,839
and what they can teach us about level design.

10
00:00:24,319 --> 00:00:27,062
Specifically, what they can teach us about level geometry.

11
00:00:28,262 --> 00:00:31,205
Before we get too far into details, let's get academic.

12
00:00:32,107 --> 00:00:36,351
Playgrounds are persistent community spaces for non-prescriptive play.

13
00:00:37,072 --> 00:00:41,816
Playgrounds are not an obstacle course to beat, or a puzzle to solve, or a story to tell.

14
00:00:42,337 --> 00:00:45,620
There are aspects of obstacle courses and stories to playgrounds,

15
00:00:45,960 --> 00:00:49,304
but playgrounds are not consumed through interaction. They persist.

16
00:00:49,784 --> 00:00:54,369
A good playground facilitates many stories, many obstacle courses, and many forms of play.

17
00:00:55,351 --> 00:00:57,852
Playgrounds are also fundamentally multiplayer spaces,

18
00:00:58,272 --> 00:01:00,113
and they scale according to player need.

19
00:01:00,433 --> 00:01:03,495
That means player count, game mode, and...

20
00:01:03,515 --> 00:01:06,356
Oh, I'm blanking on the third one.

21
00:01:10,303 --> 00:01:10,843
player trust.

22
00:01:11,303 --> 00:01:12,123
Next slide, of course.

23
00:01:12,924 --> 00:01:15,144
So Raf Koster and a team with Google explored the idea of a

24
00:01:15,204 --> 00:01:16,705
trust spectrum in games.

25
00:01:17,065 --> 00:01:19,526
And a similar idea also applies to playgrounds.

26
00:01:20,126 --> 00:01:23,047
Here we can scale up from solo and parallel play to

27
00:01:23,127 --> 00:01:26,068
cooperative activities and upward to large group

28
00:01:26,148 --> 00:01:27,788
competitive and cooperative activities.

29
00:01:29,050 --> 00:01:32,392
There's also some overlap between the idea of playgrounds and sandboxes.

30
00:01:32,512 --> 00:01:34,513
Often we talk about sandbox level design.

31
00:01:34,993 --> 00:01:37,254
The main difference is that sandboxes,

32
00:01:38,334 --> 00:01:40,455
it's kind of a neutral space where you bring toys.

33
00:01:40,795 --> 00:01:42,496
Playgrounds are the toy itself.

34
00:01:43,136 --> 00:01:45,717
Sandboxes are also often consumed through interaction,

35
00:01:45,897 --> 00:01:47,198
while playgrounds persist.

36
00:01:47,678 --> 00:01:50,539
Sandboxes are often really good at parallel play and solo play,

37
00:01:50,579 --> 00:01:53,820
but they don't offer the most rich cooperative or competitive experiences.

38
00:01:57,063 --> 00:02:00,607
The core of this talk is about level geometry, but keep in mind that

39
00:02:01,348 --> 00:02:04,893
the way we build our levels and the way we shape our levels affects multiplayer systems.

40
00:02:05,333 --> 00:02:09,218
If we played Deathmatch on a King of the Hill map, it would still probably feel like King of the Hill,

41
00:02:09,639 --> 00:02:11,701
because level design and game systems work together.

42
00:02:12,462 --> 00:02:14,144
So here's a playground for my neighborhood.

43
00:02:14,464 --> 00:02:16,046
It's pretty basic, pretty simple.

44
00:02:16,086 --> 00:02:19,069
If you live in North America, you've probably seen playgrounds like this all over the place.

45
00:02:19,589 --> 00:02:22,992
And the important thing here is we can't convert this layout directly to our video game levels,

46
00:02:23,012 --> 00:02:24,494
and we also probably wouldn't want to.

47
00:02:25,054 --> 00:02:26,596
But there is still something we can learn from it.

48
00:02:27,599 --> 00:02:29,341
So here's the same playground up close.

49
00:02:29,581 --> 00:02:30,402
Let's break it down.

50
00:02:31,083 --> 00:02:33,105
As the fundamental unit, we have a module,

51
00:02:33,185 --> 00:02:34,606
or a self-contained chunk.

52
00:02:35,387 --> 00:02:37,870
At the heart of this module is a platform elevated up.

53
00:02:38,631 --> 00:02:39,932
This serves as a kind of goal.

54
00:02:40,412 --> 00:02:41,954
Keep in mind this playground is for young kids.

55
00:02:42,054 --> 00:02:43,175
For me, standing on that platform

56
00:02:43,235 --> 00:02:44,657
is not a meaningful vantage point,

57
00:02:45,017 --> 00:02:46,579
but for a five-year-old, you know, it is.

58
00:02:47,731 --> 00:02:51,734
In order to get up to that platform, our goal, there's a skill check that the player must pass.

59
00:02:52,014 --> 00:02:54,596
A route up, in this case a staircase.

60
00:02:55,016 --> 00:02:58,539
The important thing to keep in mind is that the skill check is not a binary pass or fail.

61
00:02:58,599 --> 00:03:04,023
You can fail, trip and hurt yourself, but most use will depend and fall into a range of skill.

62
00:03:04,543 --> 00:03:06,745
For a three-year-old, you'll be pretty slow on those stairs.

63
00:03:06,785 --> 00:03:07,885
For a five-year-old, okay.

64
00:03:08,386 --> 00:03:10,347
For a ten-year-old, maybe you can go two steps at a time.

65
00:03:11,002 --> 00:03:13,243
And if you keep the multiplayer context in mind,

66
00:03:13,783 --> 00:03:15,444
if I can take those stairs two steps at a time

67
00:03:15,484 --> 00:03:16,584
and my opponent can't,

68
00:03:16,905 --> 00:03:18,425
now I've got tactics I can exploit.

69
00:03:19,826 --> 00:03:21,067
Now that we've reached the platform,

70
00:03:21,127 --> 00:03:23,668
we have routes back down, and these function as rewards,

71
00:03:23,928 --> 00:03:25,189
in this case, slides.

72
00:03:25,749 --> 00:03:27,490
These are also opportunities for subversive play

73
00:03:27,530 --> 00:03:29,651
for the skillful player who can run up the slide.

74
00:03:30,771 --> 00:03:32,912
Subversive play is basically whenever a constraint

75
00:03:32,932 --> 00:03:34,933
of the design can be used against its intent,

76
00:03:35,133 --> 00:03:36,634
or when the player thinks they're doing something

77
00:03:36,674 --> 00:03:38,575
against intent, whether or not it actually was.

78
00:03:39,865 --> 00:03:41,886
Hard to see, but there's also a set piece in the back.

79
00:03:41,926 --> 00:03:43,066
This is a little steering wheel.

80
00:03:43,566 --> 00:03:46,007
A good set piece helps for landmarking

81
00:03:46,307 --> 00:03:47,647
and theming a module.

82
00:03:49,167 --> 00:03:51,008
Cool, so now that we have this language of modules,

83
00:03:51,048 --> 00:03:53,108
we can build into more complex structures.

84
00:03:53,688 --> 00:03:55,169
So this playground's a little more interesting

85
00:03:55,389 --> 00:03:56,769
because here we have several modules

86
00:03:56,789 --> 00:03:58,349
that combine into a larger structure.

87
00:03:58,929 --> 00:03:59,710
As our first module,

88
00:03:59,750 --> 00:04:01,490
we have a staircase going around the right.

89
00:04:01,830 --> 00:04:03,710
We've got a rock wall that we're seeing the back of,

90
00:04:03,770 --> 00:04:04,891
and we've got some slides.

91
00:04:05,471 --> 00:04:06,611
This connects to a second module

92
00:04:06,651 --> 00:04:08,911
with this sort of twisted ladder pole thing.

93
00:04:09,632 --> 00:04:14,839
This goes up to a third module with a twisty tube slide, a long slide, a ladder going down

94
00:04:14,859 --> 00:04:16,402
the interior and a big rock wall.

95
00:04:16,802 --> 00:04:21,128
And that ladder connects to our fourth module with a small staircase, some monkey bars and

96
00:04:21,148 --> 00:04:22,170
a little jump up stump.

97
00:04:22,671 --> 00:04:23,872
And that takes us back to the ground.

98
00:04:25,110 --> 00:04:26,651
In the abstract, if we rearrange this,

99
00:04:26,691 --> 00:04:29,251
we see this formula is a hierarchy, or trees.

100
00:04:30,091 --> 00:04:31,552
As a playground, it's pretty cool,

101
00:04:31,592 --> 00:04:33,072
but it's also still pretty simple.

102
00:04:33,292 --> 00:04:34,852
If we played a game of tag here,

103
00:04:35,212 --> 00:04:36,653
the lack of loops would be a problem.

104
00:04:37,113 --> 00:04:38,393
We'd reach one end of the structure,

105
00:04:38,413 --> 00:04:40,173
and the only way to go back to the other end

106
00:04:40,513 --> 00:04:42,414
would be to run around on the ground or backtrack.

107
00:04:43,134 --> 00:04:44,554
But now that we have this abstract language,

108
00:04:44,574 --> 00:04:46,195
it's pretty easy to imagine a version

109
00:04:46,255 --> 00:04:47,475
that connects as cycles.

110
00:04:48,015 --> 00:04:49,335
In fact, now with this abstract language,

111
00:04:49,375 --> 00:04:51,876
we can imagine infinite, sprawling, huge playgrounds

112
00:04:51,916 --> 00:04:52,576
if we so wanted.

113
00:04:54,438 --> 00:04:57,519
How do we convert this to level geometry and level design?

114
00:04:58,539 --> 00:04:59,820
Here is where we get to modding.

115
00:05:00,860 --> 00:05:03,761
Most of my experiments have been for Quake, the one from 1996.

116
00:05:04,901 --> 00:05:05,841
For those of you who do not know,

117
00:05:05,881 --> 00:05:07,942
that is a screenshot of the first level in Quake.

118
00:05:11,883 --> 00:05:14,224
When applying Playgrounds, the really important thing

119
00:05:14,264 --> 00:05:16,765
is that we have a robust skill set to draw on,

120
00:05:17,045 --> 00:05:17,765
that we can apply.

121
00:05:18,972 --> 00:05:19,933
and Quake has that.

122
00:05:20,593 --> 00:05:22,094
Quake also has advanced skill checks

123
00:05:22,134 --> 00:05:23,315
for its movement systems,

124
00:05:23,375 --> 00:05:24,596
which we'll get to in a little bit.

125
00:05:25,096 --> 00:05:26,597
There's also an active player community,

126
00:05:26,637 --> 00:05:28,639
which means there's a lot of feedback that we can get.

127
00:05:28,659 --> 00:05:31,941
The maps are also fundamentally multiplayer

128
00:05:32,001 --> 00:05:33,802
in that they support solo, cooperative,

129
00:05:33,902 --> 00:05:35,303
and PVP on all maps.

130
00:05:35,963 --> 00:05:37,084
Once we adjust the layouts

131
00:05:37,324 --> 00:05:38,905
to be more in the playground format,

132
00:05:39,446 --> 00:05:41,887
we have something that's much closer

133
00:05:41,927 --> 00:05:43,348
to the playgrounds I've described

134
00:05:43,408 --> 00:05:45,349
than many other games that exist.

135
00:05:46,336 --> 00:05:48,938
So taking those ideas together, here's a basic playground.

136
00:05:49,479 --> 00:05:50,640
Again, if you've played Quake,

137
00:05:51,281 --> 00:05:52,502
if you looked at the other screenshot,

138
00:05:52,522 --> 00:05:54,163
this looks nothing like a normal Quake level,

139
00:05:54,183 --> 00:05:55,344
but this is a Quake level.

140
00:05:56,525 --> 00:05:59,928
And once we overlay and break it back down

141
00:06:00,029 --> 00:06:02,431
into the ideas of modules and the skills involved,

142
00:06:02,771 --> 00:06:04,473
this should look familiar by now.

143
00:06:05,634 --> 00:06:07,595
Rearranged, and if we swapped out those skills,

144
00:06:07,655 --> 00:06:11,479
the same hierarchy and loops could describe a playground.

145
00:06:12,567 --> 00:06:15,608
Pushing these ideas further, adding monsters and items

146
00:06:15,648 --> 00:06:17,068
for more rewards and skill checks,

147
00:06:17,088 --> 00:06:18,609
and we get some pretty neat playgrounds.

148
00:06:19,189 --> 00:06:21,910
Importantly, once we add enemy respawning

149
00:06:21,950 --> 00:06:23,910
and item respawning persistence,

150
00:06:24,770 --> 00:06:26,271
this level becomes a place to be

151
00:06:26,351 --> 00:06:28,031
rather than an obstacle course to complete,

152
00:06:28,131 --> 00:06:29,131
like most Quake levels.

153
00:06:30,272 --> 00:06:32,472
Importantly, while there are objectives to complete,

154
00:06:32,792 --> 00:06:34,153
there are many ways to achieve them

155
00:06:34,253 --> 00:06:36,693
and many ways of adding new goals and new ways of playing.

156
00:06:36,713 --> 00:06:39,614
This is a test.

157
00:06:45,190 --> 00:06:48,933
So the player got a ring of shadows, which means the monsters aren't seeing them.

158
00:06:48,953 --> 00:06:52,115
Normally the ring of shadows only lasts about 30 seconds, which wouldn't be enough to beat

159
00:06:52,135 --> 00:06:56,058
the level, but this player is also doing crazy stuff.

160
00:06:56,358 --> 00:06:56,658
So...

161
00:06:56,698 --> 00:07:06,525
Alright, there you go.

162
00:07:08,354 --> 00:07:12,635
The speedrun, normally that map takes about 10 to 15 minutes for a first playthrough to go through,

163
00:07:13,195 --> 00:07:18,596
but in the speedrun, using the advanced skill checks of rocket jumping, circle jumping, ramp jumping,

164
00:07:18,636 --> 00:07:20,457
a player is able to beat it in 27 seconds.

165
00:07:21,057 --> 00:07:25,538
And that's not something I planned, but it's something that's possible within this playground format.

166
00:07:26,298 --> 00:07:29,899
And it's a way of adding new goals and new ways of playing on top of the experience

167
00:07:29,979 --> 00:07:35,481
that are separate from what would traditionally be a standard obstacle course.

168
00:07:36,577 --> 00:07:38,058
At this point, some of you may be thinking,

169
00:07:38,618 --> 00:07:40,339
but Andrew, I'm not making that kind of game.

170
00:07:40,419 --> 00:07:41,559
How does this help me?

171
00:07:42,340 --> 00:07:44,120
And the reality is that probably you aren't making

172
00:07:44,160 --> 00:07:46,701
this kind of game because this is a very strange thing

173
00:07:46,721 --> 00:07:47,522
I'm exploring.

174
00:07:48,142 --> 00:07:50,463
But if you are working in 3D environments

175
00:07:50,583 --> 00:07:51,763
and you have player avatars,

176
00:07:51,943 --> 00:07:53,964
and you're worried about camera, character, and controls,

177
00:07:54,384 --> 00:07:56,165
then you can still apply Playgrounds.

178
00:07:57,039 --> 00:08:02,182
If you're involved in prototyping or early pre-production, you need metrics test maps.

179
00:08:02,682 --> 00:08:06,725
The standard metrics test map is basically just a 3D equivalent of a meter stick.

180
00:08:06,825 --> 00:08:09,726
It tells you how far, how fast, how high, and so on.

181
00:08:10,447 --> 00:08:12,688
But it doesn't tell you whether your metrics are fun.

182
00:08:13,569 --> 00:08:14,949
So, metrics playgrounds.

183
00:08:16,224 --> 00:08:19,126
Here's an example of a metrics playground I built for a game

184
00:08:19,186 --> 00:08:21,608
where we wanted to get the fundamentals right very early on.

185
00:08:22,069 --> 00:08:25,191
We had a lot of fundamental rich moveset

186
00:08:25,552 --> 00:08:26,312
that we wanted to explore.

187
00:08:26,352 --> 00:08:28,174
We had a tight third-person camera,

188
00:08:28,214 --> 00:08:30,556
we had double jumping, clambering, crouching,

189
00:08:31,036 --> 00:08:32,717
sliding, sprinting, all sorts of things.

190
00:08:32,737 --> 00:08:34,519
We wanted to make sure that all those things

191
00:08:34,599 --> 00:08:37,762
worked cohesively and none of those abilities

192
00:08:37,822 --> 00:08:39,063
stood out as sore thumbs.

193
00:08:40,652 --> 00:08:42,433
As we started adding more gameplay mechanics

194
00:08:42,473 --> 00:08:43,734
and discovering what our game was,

195
00:08:43,774 --> 00:08:45,316
we dropped them into the level as well.

196
00:08:45,776 --> 00:08:47,698
We had gunplay, so there were things to shoot at

197
00:08:47,718 --> 00:08:48,799
and things that shot at you.

198
00:08:48,839 --> 00:08:52,302
And this was a way to sample the entire experience

199
00:08:52,342 --> 00:08:53,903
of the game in one spot.

200
00:08:54,924 --> 00:08:57,166
Would our final levels look anything like Playgrounds?

201
00:08:57,847 --> 00:08:59,768
Probably not, and that's okay.

202
00:09:00,449 --> 00:09:03,191
The value of Playgrounds here was to help us identify

203
00:09:03,211 --> 00:09:05,493
the fun of the game rather than worrying

204
00:09:05,533 --> 00:09:08,576
about the level design just yet.

205
00:09:10,500 --> 00:09:12,401
Returning to our idea of playgrounds,

206
00:09:12,961 --> 00:09:15,721
I've really only scratched the surface with my example so far.

207
00:09:16,762 --> 00:09:18,802
Really, we've gotten at the non-prescriptive aspect

208
00:09:18,862 --> 00:09:21,303
through our approach to level geometry.

209
00:09:21,703 --> 00:09:25,063
There's a lot more work to be done around the persistent community spaces as well.

210
00:09:26,144 --> 00:09:28,444
To me, playgrounds are an interesting metaphor

211
00:09:28,824 --> 00:09:31,185
for what we can do with level design around multiplayer.

212
00:09:31,765 --> 00:09:35,645
It's an example of how level geometry affects system design.

213
00:09:36,306 --> 00:09:37,826
And it's a way for level geometry

214
00:09:38,559 --> 00:09:41,520
to allow multiplayer to be more flexible to our players' needs.

