I built as an experiment an alternative controller

502
00:25:55,857 --> 00:25:59,279
to shift the style of play from deep mental focus

503
00:25:59,640 --> 00:26:01,381
to an embodied form of play.

504
00:26:03,179 --> 00:26:07,121
So I created cardboard wings, put tilt switches

505
00:26:07,281 --> 00:26:08,662
on the ends of them for steering,

506
00:26:09,283 --> 00:26:10,864
buttons at the end of the wings for firing,

507
00:26:11,084 --> 00:26:12,665
and a foot pedal to accelerate.

508
00:26:13,186 --> 00:26:15,487
And this is to get people to embrace

509
00:26:15,547 --> 00:26:17,008
the external experience.

510
00:26:17,329 --> 00:26:20,391
It was an entirely new feeling and a lot of fun

511
00:26:20,431 --> 00:26:21,792
to both play and watch.

512
00:26:22,732 --> 00:26:25,414
It became a fundamentally different experience,

513
00:26:25,454 --> 00:26:28,597
similar to what we sports accomplished when

514
00:26:28,637 --> 00:26:29,757
playing games like tennis.

515
00:26:31,038 --> 00:26:34,440
We found that failure was a lot more fun,

516
00:26:35,101 --> 00:26:37,362
and it actually shifted the skills needed

517
00:26:37,602 --> 00:26:38,823
to be good at the game.

518
00:26:39,263 --> 00:26:42,686
So it was a great spectacle, but also very exhausting.

519
00:26:44,267 --> 00:26:46,288
So I think it's also good to take a look at other mediums

520
00:26:46,408 --> 00:26:48,669
and communities and fandoms for how they reduce

521
00:26:48,689 --> 00:26:51,031
the contradictions in their experiences,

522
00:26:51,291 --> 00:26:53,072
and how they transition their audiences

523
00:26:53,132 --> 00:26:55,774
to fully say yes to the designed reality,

524
00:26:56,074 --> 00:26:58,776
whether it be a game, a film, or whatever it happens to be.

525
00:26:59,336 --> 00:27:03,440
A Rocky Horror audience goes much deeper than simply putting on costumes.

526
00:27:03,840 --> 00:27:07,644
Many bring an array of props like rice and rubber gloves and noisemakers.

527
00:27:08,425 --> 00:27:12,909
Some venues or events will even provide some of these props so that people that are new

528
00:27:12,949 --> 00:27:16,292
to these experiences are more encouraged to get involved.

529
00:27:16,652 --> 00:27:20,555
and be fully prepared for when that film begins.

530
00:27:21,736 --> 00:27:24,317
Now the boundary in this case is the film itself.

531
00:27:24,617 --> 00:27:26,138
It's what's displayed on the screen.

532
00:27:26,839 --> 00:27:28,680
You could just walk into the theater, sit down,

533
00:27:28,700 --> 00:27:31,742
they press play, and bam, there you go.

534
00:27:31,982 --> 00:27:34,444
But it's these other acts, these influences

535
00:27:34,544 --> 00:27:38,566
that change that bleed that makes it much more enjoyable

536
00:27:38,606 --> 00:27:40,428
and a really special thing for the fans.

537
00:27:41,409 --> 00:27:44,533
There's a lot of places that are exploring this in a lot of really

538
00:27:44,553 --> 00:27:47,416
interesting ways beyond just theme parks.

539
00:27:47,576 --> 00:27:50,840
Meow Wolf in Phoenix with immersive art and storytelling.

540
00:27:51,581 --> 00:27:53,723
Sleep No More in New York with immersive theater.

541
00:27:54,164 --> 00:27:57,588
Two Bit Circus in LA, a modern arcade with amusements and

542
00:27:57,648 --> 00:27:59,670
layers of metagames throughout the space.

543
00:28:00,532 --> 00:28:02,455
or Can Can Wonderland and the Twin Cities,

544
00:28:02,475 --> 00:28:05,961
which has artist-designed mini-golf, unique games,

545
00:28:06,181 --> 00:28:08,064
and interesting entertainment experiences.

546
00:28:08,585 --> 00:28:10,108
And of course, Escape Rooms,

547
00:28:10,368 --> 00:28:12,813
which have become an entire industry unto themselves.

548
00:28:13,900 --> 00:28:16,101
But escape rooms are often the most guilty

549
00:28:16,482 --> 00:28:18,343
in not considering the experience bleed.

550
00:28:18,683 --> 00:28:19,804
The boundary is obvious.

551
00:28:20,345 --> 00:28:22,086
The door opens, you put in the room,

552
00:28:22,146 --> 00:28:24,528
the door closes, the clock starts, bam, there you go.

553
00:28:25,589 --> 00:28:27,550
This is actually the first escape room I designed

554
00:28:27,570 --> 00:28:30,612
called Utopia Room, and we managed to win an award for it,

555
00:28:30,632 --> 00:28:31,273
which was awesome.

556
00:28:31,693 --> 00:28:36,717
But sadly, my influence stopped at the boundary.

557
00:28:37,258 --> 00:28:41,743
And I had no ability for that experience to bleed beyond that door.

558
00:28:41,763 --> 00:28:46,768
And for players, the experience when going to something like an escape room

559
00:28:46,908 --> 00:28:50,272
begins long before they enter that room.

560
00:28:50,573 --> 00:28:53,316
It may be when they finally find a parking spot.

561
00:28:53,376 --> 00:28:54,697
It may even be before then.

562
00:28:55,058 --> 00:28:56,779
They're in a state of anticipation.

563
00:28:57,620 --> 00:29:01,604
which is a really perfect state for designers to start whispering in their ears.

564
00:29:02,044 --> 00:29:08,609
But without any influence, it's also really easy for players to put them in a state that is not conducive for that,

565
00:29:08,970 --> 00:29:10,611
and you end up with something really jarring.

566
00:29:11,052 --> 00:29:14,134
So in this case, the onboarding, I think, is really, really important,

567
00:29:14,174 --> 00:29:18,678
to help them forget the world they came from and be prepared to enter that new one.

568
00:29:20,582 --> 00:29:23,324
So the bleed being ignored really hurt the experience

569
00:29:24,145 --> 00:29:25,406
even after the boundary.

570
00:29:26,266 --> 00:29:28,148
Personally, I would have a lot of trouble adjusting

571
00:29:28,408 --> 00:29:31,330
if I open a closet, suddenly stumbled into Narnia

572
00:29:31,390 --> 00:29:32,431
without so much as a coat,

573
00:29:32,851 --> 00:29:35,032
Tumnus appears, tells me that I have 60 minutes

574
00:29:35,072 --> 00:29:36,774
to keep the White Witch from killing us all.

575
00:29:37,694 --> 00:29:39,576
First five minutes, I'd just be sputtering around

576
00:29:39,636 --> 00:29:43,098
trying to get my bearings, and I want that 60 minutes.

577
00:29:43,418 --> 00:29:47,181
I want all 60 minutes to be fulfilling and engaging

578
00:29:47,281 --> 00:29:49,102
and not stressful and jarring.

579
00:29:50,143 --> 00:29:52,885
So I'm not saying that you're not already doing a lot of these things,

580
00:29:53,566 --> 00:29:56,888
but that looking at the experiences you design through some of these lenses

581
00:29:57,429 --> 00:29:59,310
can help you notice spots that you've missed

582
00:29:59,791 --> 00:30:02,313
or areas that you haven't been paying attention to before,

583
00:30:02,853 --> 00:30:08,698
not to mention as more and more devices collect in our homes and all around us

584
00:30:08,878 --> 00:30:13,222
with Internet of Things and smart lights and TV reactive LEDs

585
00:30:13,282 --> 00:30:15,183
and smart speakers and who knows what else.

586
00:30:15,904 --> 00:30:20,985
There are going to be more and more ways for designers to reach out of the digital into

587
00:30:21,005 --> 00:30:24,266
the physical world and put more and more influence.

588
00:30:25,306 --> 00:30:30,808
So imagine a software update where you can approve your Switch to talk to your Hue light

589
00:30:30,848 --> 00:30:34,589
bulbs and set the mood a bit when you're playing Breath of the Wild.

590
00:30:35,619 --> 00:30:37,901
And maybe they stick a projector on the back of your TV

591
00:30:37,961 --> 00:30:40,763
so the weather pattern is always on your ceiling.

592
00:30:40,823 --> 00:30:43,385
So you get that nice, warm, beautiful sunny day

593
00:30:43,845 --> 00:30:47,488
or the ominous clouds rolling in and things can get spooky.

594
00:30:48,461 --> 00:30:50,062
And maybe this is really dumb.

595
00:30:51,082 --> 00:30:53,224
But it also kind of seems a little fun, too.

596
00:30:53,244 --> 00:30:56,025
And I think it's worth continuing

597
00:30:56,065 --> 00:30:58,807
to reevaluate these things and look at what's possible,

598
00:30:58,887 --> 00:31:01,909
whether you design in real spaces like myself

599
00:31:02,229 --> 00:31:03,529
or in the digital.

600
00:31:03,930 --> 00:31:06,731
And as consoles change and what we plan changes,

601
00:31:06,851 --> 00:31:07,952
other tech is gonna change.

602
00:31:08,192 --> 00:31:09,933
We'll be able to use a lot more of this tech

603
00:31:10,033 --> 00:31:13,435
and blur that boundary between the digital and the rest.

604
00:31:14,175 --> 00:31:15,916
This is a game I created called Cylindrus.

605
00:31:16,056 --> 00:31:21,218
It's a four-player wireless game with a 2D field wrapped

606
00:31:21,278 --> 00:31:23,919
around a cylinder, creating this continuous space.

607
00:31:24,419 --> 00:31:26,440
So the real world, in this case, becomes

608
00:31:26,620 --> 00:31:27,780
part of the constraints.

609
00:31:27,920 --> 00:31:29,641
It becomes part of the mechanics.

610
00:31:30,621 --> 00:31:33,823
The level itself has to exist on a physical space

611
00:31:33,983 --> 00:31:36,184
and therefore cannot be infinite.

612
00:31:37,664 --> 00:31:43,191
And this forces you to incorporate moving around that digital or virtual world

613
00:31:43,291 --> 00:31:44,913
in order to better understand it.

614
00:31:45,374 --> 00:31:48,978
But essentially, it's still just a video game slapped onto a cylinder.

615
00:31:50,450 --> 00:31:52,131
This is one called Please Stand By.

616
00:31:52,211 --> 00:31:54,052
It's a 1950s television set

617
00:31:54,933 --> 00:31:57,534
with a completely digital component,

618
00:31:57,815 --> 00:32:00,316
but all of the interface is using the physical

619
00:32:00,556 --> 00:32:04,559
and the rabbit ears, the hitting the side of the TV,

620
00:32:04,699 --> 00:32:05,539
using the knobs.

621
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:09,882
It stands out because it is out of place in time,

622
00:32:10,062 --> 00:32:11,202
but not in space.

623
00:32:11,583 --> 00:32:14,464
It's a familiar artifact that belongs in a space.

624
00:32:15,165 --> 00:32:18,048
So even though the game is digital and just made in Unity,

625
00:32:18,068 --> 00:32:20,951
it could be played without any of those other components,

626
00:32:21,291 --> 00:32:24,555
the controls for this experience live within the bleed.

627
00:32:25,015 --> 00:32:27,418
And that experience will bleed into your memories

628
00:32:27,738 --> 00:32:30,141
related to such a familiar artifact.

629
00:32:30,981 --> 00:32:37,104
I want to leave you with the final thought of how do you use the space between your players

630
00:32:37,324 --> 00:32:39,685
and your game, because it does not have to be empty.

631
00:32:40,405 --> 00:32:44,827
Think about where the boundary is for what you have created, that point where you have

632
00:32:44,987 --> 00:32:50,309
full control, and then think about what happens before there and how people come up to that.

633
00:32:51,590 --> 00:32:52,250
Thank you very much.

634
00:32:52,270 --> 00:32:53,311
Yeah.

635
00:32:53,331 --> 00:32:53,771
Thank you.

636
00:33:00,516 --> 00:33:04,294
So if anybody has any questions, hopefully we have a couple of minutes.

637
00:33:04,394 --> 00:33:05,258
But yeah.

